SIMPLE: ossify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ossify
<hw>Os"si*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ossified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Ossifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>os</ets>, <ets>ossis</ets>, bone + <ets>-fy</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>ossifier</ets>. See <er>Osseous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To form into bone; to change from a soft
animal substance into bone, as by the deposition of lime
salts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>: <def>To harden; <as>as, to
<ex>ossify</ex> the heart</as>.</def> <rj><au>Ruskin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ossify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ossify
<hw>Os"si*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To become
bone; to change from a soft tissue to a hard bony tissue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ossifying</ent>⟦br⟧
